# Pattern Matching Utility

This project uses a custom pattern matching utility inspired by functional programming languages like Rust and F#. The `match` function provides type-safe, composable pattern matching for conditional logic.

## Core Concepts

### Match Function

The `match` function creates a pattern matcher for any input value:

```typescript
import { match } from "@/utils/match";

const result = match(inputValue)
  .with(pattern1, handler1)
  .with(pattern2, handler2)
  .default(defaultHandler);
```

### Pattern Types

#### Value Patterns

Match exact values:

```typescript
const status = "loading";

const message = match(status)
  .with("loading", () => "Please wait...")
  .with("success", () => "Operation completed")
  .with("error", () => "Something went wrong")
  .default(() => "Unknown status");
```

#### Predicate Patterns

Use functions for complex conditions:

```typescript
const score = 85;

const grade = match(score)
  .with(
    (s) => s >= 90,
    () => "A"
  )
  .with(
    (s) => s >= 80,
    () => "B"
  )
  .with(
    (s) => s >= 70,
    () => "C"
  )
  .with(
    (s) => s >= 60,
    () => "D"
  )
  .default(() => "F");
```

#### Type Patterns

Match different types:

```typescript
const processValue = (value: string | number | boolean) => {
  return match(value)
    .with(
      (v): v is string => typeof v === "string",
      (v) => v.toUpperCase()
    )
    .with(
      (v): v is number => typeof v === "number",
      (v) => v * 2
    )
    .with(
      (v): v is boolean => typeof v === "boolean",
      (v) => (v ? "Yes" : "No")
    )
    .default(() => "Unknown type");
};
```

## Advanced Usage

### Chaining Patterns

Patterns are evaluated in order, and the first match is used:

```typescript
const processUser = (user: User) => {
  return match(user)
    .with(
      (u) => u.role === "admin",
      (u) => `Admin: ${u.name}`
    )
    .with(
      (u) => u.role === "user",
      (u) => `User: ${u.name}`
    )
    .with(
      (u) => u.isActive,
      (u) => `Active: ${u.name}`
    )
    .default((u) => `Inactive: ${u.name}`);
};
```

### Complex Object Matching

```typescript
interface ApiResponse {
  status: "success" | "error";
  data?: unknown;
  error?: string;
}

const handleApiResponse = (response: ApiResponse) => {
  return match(response)
    .with(
      (r) => r.status === "success" && r.data !== undefined,
      (r) => `Success: ${JSON.stringify(r.data)}`
    )
    .with(
      (r) => r.status === "error" && r.error !== undefined,
      (r) => `Error: ${r.error}`
    )
    .default(() => "Unknown response format");
};
```

### Result Pattern Integration

Combine with Result pattern for robust error handling:

```typescript
import { match } from "@/utils/match";
import { ok, err, Result } from "@/utils/result";

const processResult = <T, E>(result: Result<T, E>) => {
  return match(result)
    .with(
      (r) => r.success === true,
      (r) => `Success: ${JSON.stringify(r.data)}`
    )
    .with(
      (r) => r.success === false,
      (r) => `Error: ${r.error}`
    )
    .default(() => "Unknown result format");
};
```

## When Helper

The `when` helper provides boolean pattern matching:

```typescript
import { when } from "@/utils/match";

const message = when(isLoading)
  .with(true, () => "Loading...")
  .with(false, () => "Ready")
  .default(() => "Unknown state");
```

## Best Practices

### 1. Use Descriptive Patterns

```typescript
// ✅ Good: Clear, descriptive patterns
const getStatusMessage = (status: string) => {
  return match(status)
    .with("pending", () => "Request is being processed")
    .with("approved", () => "Request has been approved")
    .with("rejected", () => "Request has been rejected")
    .default(() => "Unknown status");
};

// ❌ Bad: Unclear patterns
const getStatusMessage = (status: string) => {
  return match(status)
    .with("p", () => "Processing")
    .with("a", () => "Approved")
    .with("r", () => "Rejected")
    .default(() => "Unknown");
};
```

### 2. Extract Complex Logic

```typescript
// ✅ Good: Extract complex patterns
const isHighPriority = (task: Task) =>
  task.priority === "high" || task.isUrgent;

const processTask = (task: Task) => {
  return match(task)
    .with(isHighPriority, (t) => `High priority: ${t.title}`)
    .with(
      (t) => t.priority === "medium",
      (t) => `Medium: ${t.title}`
    )
    .with(
      (t) => t.priority === "low",
      (t) => `Low: ${t.title}`
    )
    .default((t) => `Unknown priority: ${t.title}`);
};

// ❌ Bad: Inline complex logic
const processTask = (task: Task) => {
  return match(task)
    .with(
      (t) => t.priority === "high" || t.isUrgent,
      (t) => `High priority: ${t.title}`
    )
    .with(
      (t) => t.priority === "medium",
      (t) => `Medium: ${t.title}`
    )
    .with(
      (t) => t.priority === "low",
      (t) => `Low: ${t.title}`
    )
    .default((t) => `Unknown priority: ${t.title}`);
};
```

### 3. Always Provide Default Cases

```typescript
// ✅ Good: Always handle default case
const getErrorMessage = (error: Error) => {
  return match(error.constructor.name)
    .with("ValidationError", () => "Please check your input")
    .with("NetworkError", () => "Connection failed")
    .with("AuthError", () => "Authentication required")
    .default(() => "An unexpected error occurred");
};

// ❌ Bad: Missing default case (will throw)
const getErrorMessage = (error: Error) => {
  return match(error.constructor.name)
    .with("ValidationError", () => "Please check your input")
    .with("NetworkError", () => "Connection failed")
    .with("AuthError", () => "Authentication required");
};
```

### 4. Use Type Guards for Type Safety

```typescript
// ✅ Good: Use type guards
const processValue = (value: unknown) => {
  return match(value)
    .with(
      (v): v is string => typeof v === "string",
      (v) => v.length
    )
    .with(
      (v): v is number => typeof v === "number",
      (v) => v * 2
    )
    .with(
      (v): v is boolean => typeof v === "boolean",
      (v) => (v ? 1 : 0)
    )
    .default(() => 0);
};

// ❌ Bad: No type safety
const processValue = (value: unknown) => {
  return match(value)
    .with("string", (v) => (v as string).length)
    .with("number", (v) => (v as number) * 2)
    .with("boolean", (v) => ((v as boolean) ? 1 : 0))
    .default(() => 0);
};
```

### 5. Combine with Early Returns

```typescript
// ✅ Good: Combine with early returns
const processUser = (user: User | null) => {
  if (!user) {
    return "No user provided";
  }

  return match(user.status)
    .with("active", () => `Welcome back, ${user.name}`)
    .with("inactive", () => "Account is inactive")
    .with("banned", () => "Account has been banned")
    .default(() => "Unknown account status");
};

// ❌ Bad: Nested conditions
const processUser = (user: User | null) => {
  return match(user)
    .with(null, () => "No user provided")
    .with(
      (u) => u !== null && u.status === "active",
      (u) => `Welcome back, ${u!.name}`
    )
    .with(
      (u) => u !== null && u.status === "inactive",
      () => "Account is inactive"
    )
    .with(
      (u) => u !== null && u.status === "banned",
      () => "Account has been banned"
    )
    .default(() => "Unknown account status");
};
```

## Common Patterns

### API Response Handling

```typescript
const handleApiResponse = <T>(response: ApiResponse<T>) => {
  return match(response)
    .with(
      (r) => r.status === 200 && r.data !== undefined,
      (r) => ok(r.data)
    )
    .with(
      (r) => r.status >= 400 && r.status < 500,
      (r) => err(new ClientError(r.message))
    )
    .with(
      (r) => r.status >= 500,
      (r) => err(new ServerError(r.message))
    )
    .default(() => err(new UnknownError("Unexpected response")));
};
```

### State Machine

```typescript
type State = "idle" | "loading" | "success" | "error";

const nextState = (currentState: State, action: string) => {
  return match([currentState, action] as const)
    .with(["idle", "start"], () => "loading" as const)
    .with(["loading", "success"], () => "success" as const)
    .with(["loading", "error"], () => "error" as const)
    .with(["success", "reset"], () => "idle" as const)
    .with(["error", "retry"], () => "loading" as const)
    .default(() => currentState);
};
```

### Validation

```typescript
const validateInput = (input: unknown) => {
  return match(input)
    .with(
      (i): i is string => typeof i === "string" && i.length > 0,
      (i) => ok(i.trim())
    )
    .with(
      (i): i is number => typeof i === "number" && !isNaN(i),
      (i) => ok(i.toString())
    )
    .default(() => err(new ValidationError("Invalid input type")));
};
```

## Performance Considerations

- Pattern matching is evaluated in order - put most common patterns first
- Use simple value patterns when possible for better performance
- Complex predicate functions are called for each pattern until a match is found
- Consider extracting complex predicates to avoid recreation on each call

## Integration with Project Patterns

This pattern matching utility integrates seamlessly with:

- **Result Pattern**: Handle success/error states with type safety
- **Functional Programming**: Compose operations without side effects
- **Type Safety**: Leverage TypeScript's type system for compile-time safety
- **Error Handling**: Provide clear, explicit error handling paths

Remember: Pattern matching should make code more readable and maintainable. If the pattern matching becomes too complex, consider refactoring into smaller, more focused functions.
